result.execSummary:
The defendant Julia M Hinkston was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess Drug Paraphernalia. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Fine to be paid within 30 days; alternate civil judgment for non payment

records.addlTxt:
9:16 AM Defendant Julia M Hinkston in court.  Prosecuting attorney Alyssa M Jay in court for the State of Wisconsin. 

Defense acknowledges receipt of complaint and waives reading of complaint. 
Service admitted/advised of charges and potential penalties. 

Prosecuting attorney and Defendant stipulate to the amended charge of Possession of Drug Paraphernalia contrary to section 13.102(c)(14)  of the Waukesha County Code of Ordinances.  
Court approves amendment.  No contest plea entered.  Court finds the defendant guilty.  
Court orders the following fine:
$267.50 to be paid within 30 days or civil judgment entered for penalty for non payment of fine.
State's Demand for Discovery and Inspection and Notice of Intent to Use Defendant's Statement and DNA Evidence.
